  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts wear different colored space suits for specific purposes related to their missions and environments:\n\n1. **White Space Suits (Extravehicular Mobility Unit - EMU)**:\n   - **Purpose**: The white suits are primarily used for spacewalks (extravehicular activities or EVAs). \n   - **Thermal Control**: The white color helps reflect sunlight and minimizes heat absorption, which is crucial in the extreme temperatures of space.\n   - **Visibility**: White suits are also more visible against the dark backdrop of space, which is important for safety and tracking during spacewalks.\n\n2. **Orange Space Suits (Advanced Crew Escape Suit - ACES)**:\n   - **Purpose**: The orange suits are designed for launch and re-entry. They provide protection and support for astronauts in case of an emergency, such as a cabin depressurization.\n   - **High Visibility**: The bright orange color makes the suits highly visible, which is beneficial for search and rescue operations in case of a water landing or other emergencies.\n   - **Safety Features**: These suits are equipped with features such as a helmet, gloves, and life support systems to ensure astronaut safety during high-risk phases of the mission.\n\nIn summary, the color and design of space suits are tailored to the specific needs of the mission, focusing on safety, thermal regulation, and visibility in different environments.",
